HONEY GARLIC BALSAMIC AIR-FRYER CHICKEN 😋

O M G- You have got to try this recipe! I’m telling you this chicken tastes SO much better in the air fryer. 

Do you own an air fryer?  Which brand and how do you like it? Let me know in the comments ⬇️⬇️

SERVES 4
INGREDIENTS 

4 chicken breast 
3 tablespoon olive oil
1/4 cup balsamic vinegar
2 tablespoon honey
3 cloves garlic, minced 
1 teaspoon onion powder
1/2 teaspoon sea salt 
1/2 teaspoon black pepper

DIRECTIONS 

In a medium-sized mixing bowl, add all of the ingredients listed above. Mix well and combine. Cover the bowl and place into the fridge to marinade for at least 30-60 minutes. 

When you are ready to cook, place your chicken breasts into your air fryer at 375-400 degrees F for 18-20 minutes on AIR FRY. (Heat will vary on brands of air fryers) 

Remove once fully cooked and slice each piece to check tenderness. YUMMO 👌🏽

MEDITERRANEAN TURKEY MEATBALLS 

On repeat because they are so delicious! I make a batch of these once per week and add them to my salad, pasta or have them as a quick protein rich snack. 

INGREDIENTS 
1 package of ground turkey
1 small onion, sautéed 
2 teaspoons tarter sauce 
1/4 cup chopped sundried tomatoes in oil
1/4 cup chopped artichokes in oil
1/3 cup crumbled feta 
1 teaspoon dried oregano (wasn’t shown) 
1 teaspoon garlic powder 
1 teaspoon onion powder 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper

DIRECTIONS 

Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F. 

In a large bowl, combine ground turkey, sautéed onion, oregano, garlic powder, garlic, tarter sauce, 1 teaspoon salt, and pepper. 

Squeeze the oil from the the sundried tomatoes and artichokes, then add them along with the feta into the mixing bowl. Mix everything well with your hands. 

Shape into 1 inch balls and place into a parchment paper lined baking sheet. 

Place into the oven for 18 minutes.

BUTTERNUT SQUASH & TURKEY CHILI 

Looking for another simple weekday dinner? You will want to save this Chili recipe for sure! If you are vegan/vegetarian, you can easily swop the turkey for crumbled tofu or quinoa. 

🌟Prep this in your instapot or crock-pot for convenience 
🌟Makes enough to serve 6-8 
🌟Makes great leftovers 
🌟Packed with protein & fibre 

INGREDIENTS 
1 medium onion, chopped
1 package ground Turkey
2 carrots, peeled & chopped
1 cup celery, chopped
1 large zucchini, chopped 
2 cups butternut squash, cubed 
2 cans fire roasted tomatoes (398 ml)
1 can stewed tomatoes (Chili flavour 540 ml) 
1 can black beans (398 ml) 
2 vegetarian boullions
4 tablespoon pre-made chili seasoning 
2 tablespoon cumin
1 teaspoon cinnamon
1/2 teaspoon fresh black pepper

DIRECTIONS 

Sauté the onions in a large pot with olive oil for 3-5 minutes. Add in the boullions and continue to stir. 

Next, add the canned tomatoes and cook for about 2 minutes. Then add the ground turkey and cook for about 5-7 minutes. Use a large spoon to break up the meat.

Add the spices and cook for an additional minute.

Add the carrots, celery, butternut squash. Stir to combine and bring the mixture to a boil. Add the zucchini and black beans last then reduce the heat to medium, cover the pot and simmer for around 30 minutes. 

Serve and enjoy!

What does it mean to “LIVE WELL?” 

Most of the time, when I ask clients what does living well mean to them, the answer is typically eating healthy or exercising more. And while these are definitely part of living well,  I try to get people to dig much deeper. I want them thinking of wellness and living a life that benefits their entire well-being. 

Health and wellness (living well), are so much more than just healthy eating and exercise! It’s how you live your life and what you engage in each day. The way you life day in and day out IS your medicine! 

I get clients to ask themselves; How do you picture your future self in 10 years from now? Are the lifestyle habits you are engaging in today, complimenting the future life you desire? 

Here is what “Living- Well” means to me; 

1. Healthy relationships

2. Letting go of the smaller things 

3. Doing something daily that makes me internally happy 

4. Enjoying food without guilt or fear

5. Focusing on my own life, less on what others do

6. Letting go of things I can’t control

7. Making an effort to get at least 7 hours of sleep each night

8. Making choices for my body without the opinion of others

9. Movement every single day- not only for strength, but for my spirit 

10. Focusing on what I have to be grateful for 

How about you? What does “Living-Well” mean to you? ⬇️

OAT BRAN BERRY MUFFINS 

6 Grams of fibre per muffin? Yes please! A great way to boost your fibre intake and tastes delicious. 

INGREDIENTS
1 1/2 cups oat bran
1 1/2 cups gluten free oat flour 
1 teaspoon cinnamon 
2 teaspoons baking powder
2 teaspoons baking soda
1/2 teaspoon salt
1/3 cup unsweetened applesauce
1/3 cup honey 
2 large eggs
1/4 cup olive oil 
1/3 cup fresh or frozen berries 

DIRECTIONS 

Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F.

Combine oat flour, oat bran, baking powder, baking soda, cinnamon and salt. Set aside. 

In a separate mixing bowl, combine the honey, apple sauce, eggs and olive oil. Mix well until smooth then pour into the dry ingredients. 

Blend well then fold the berries in last. 

Line or grease 12 muffin cups. Spoon batter into the prepared muffin cups then allow them to settle for a few minutes before putting them into the oven. 

Bake for 12-14 minutes.

5 WAYS TO STAY ON TRACK WITH YOUR HEALTH GOALS DURING THE HOLIDAY SEASON 🎄

If you are already thinking that all of your hard work and dedication towards your wellness goals are going to go out the window, I want you to remember that a few days of holiday eating & drinking will not impact your goals as much as you think! 

Try to focus on these 5 tips during this season;

1. HAVE FUN- The holiday season joins us together with loved ones and food and drinking is all apart of the experience. Rather than walking in with a restrictive, fearful mentality, simply allow yourself to enjoy a few in moderation. When you focus on what you are trying to “avoid” you will want it even more which leads to binge eating. Embrace, unchain and enjoy a bit from all. 

2. PORTION CONTROL- Like I mentioned above, restriction is not a good idea! Allow yourself to enjoy anything your heart desires, but be mindful of portion sizes— 
👊🏼👊🏼Fist full or 2 of veggies 
👋🏼Handful of protein 
🤌🏼Cupped handful of starch/carbs 
👍🏼Thumb size of fats 
❤️Always enjoy treats in moderation

3. DRINK LOTS OF WATER- Drink water all day long and especially before your meals. Hunger sometimes can be mixed up with thirst so be sure to drink that water. 

4. MOVE EVERYDAY- Try to get some form of exercise everyday. Anything works but movement during this time of year when we are surrounded by extra drinking and eating helps us feel better and make better choices. 

5. DO NOT SKIP MEALS- If you think “saving up your calories” is a good idea, you are wrong! Do not skip meals so that you can eat more later. Continue with regular healthy eating habits like a protein rich breakfast, a great big salad with protein at lunch and stay hydrated all day. This will help you make better choices at Christmas dinners. 

Above all, enjoy this time with loved ones. Food is love and pleasure that many connect around so celebrate and focus your attention less on “going off track” or what you “shouldn’t have” and more on creating memories. ❤️

Merry Christmas Eve to all! 🎄❤️

Wishing you all a very Merry Christmas & a healthy, happy New Year! 🫶🏼❤️🎄

Weight Loss & Wellness Tip Wednesday ⭐️

Have you heard the phrase, calories in vs calories out in order to lose weight? While this serves true for a typical weight loss program, what I like to educate my clients on are these points around calories;

1. Be mindful of serving size amounts & the nutritional breakdown on labels. Aim for high fibre, high protein, lower sugar counts and quality ingredients. 

2. Focus on eating whole foods and less packaged items. 

3. Keep an eye on where you might be adding additional calories (that add up) like sauces, creamer in your coffee/tea, nut butters or snack items. 

4. Release fear around commonly titled, “unhealthy” choices. Allow yourself to enjoy in moderation and be considerate of your portions.

WHAT TO LOOK FOR IN A PROTEIN POWDER? 

This is a great topic because trying to get 20-30 grams of protein at each meal can be a huge challenge. That’s where having a great protein powder can be helpful. But how to choose a healthy option? I’m breaking it down below. 

1. LOOK AT THE “FREE FROM” LIST- I prefer lactose free (easier to digest), hormone & antibiotic free, and non-GMO. 

2. SOURCED FROM? - With whey, I look for New Zealand whey, cross flow microfiltration (CFM) and from grass fed cows. Vegan protein, i’m looking for real whole, preferably fermented plants. Pea protein, hemp and brown rice are some of my favourite choices. 

3. NO FAKE SUGARS- Avoid Sucralose, aspartame, or any sugars ending in “OSE”. I like to suggest monk fruit or stevia only! 

4. PROTEIN & AMINO ACID CONTENT- You want your protein powder to have at least 20 grams (preferably more) of protein and it would be ideal if it contained all 9 essential amino acids which are the building blocks of protein and assist with cellular and muscular health. 

These protein powders are some of my favourites and I always recommend reading the labels of ALL your products to know what’s in them. A lot of protein powders are costly, so if you are on a budget, just try to choose the best one in the given situation— at least avoid the fake sugars and source a non-gmo one are my top two suggestions when on a budget. 

Do your best with nutrition and that’s all you can do. Every little bit helps! 🫶🏼

MINDFUL EATING 🍴

What is mindful eating and why is it important to practice at meal time? Mindful eating focuses on your eating  experience, sensations, thoughts, emotions and feelings about the food you are about to eat. It can be very beneficial for those with digestive issues. I know that this has helped my digestion so much! 

Here are a few ways to practice mindful eating; 

1. Think ahead on how or what you will prepare to eat that is nutritious or satisfying

2. Notice how the food looks, tastes, smells, and feels in your body as you are eating

3. Pay attention to your posture while eating

4. Avoid being distracted by your phone or surroundings

5. Focus on slow chewing and swallowing your food efficiently 

6. Pay attention to your emotions before you eat and while you eat

7. Eat slow and put your fork down between bites this way, you are more likely to notice when you are satisfied, or when you are about 80% full, so you can stop eating

Practice these habits daily for optimal digestion and health of your body 🙏🏼

3 Reasons why you may not be seeing results…. 

Results take time and dedication but most importantly, they require being consistent. 

Here are 3 main reasons why people typically do not see results when they are trying to lose weight or simply implement healthy changes into their lives; 

1. Focusing on weight/size or numbers vs just focusing on being consistent each day. If you draw your attention away from numbers and more so on what mini steps or goals you can target daily that make your body feel and function well, you will notice results. 

2. Comparing your journey, body, eating habits or results to others will set you back big time! Understand that each body is created uniquely and everyone has a different pace in which they stride. Focus on YOU and what YOUR body needs. 

3. Not monitoring portions is a HUGE one! Portion control is a key component to weight loss but also for proper digestion and becoming mindful at meals. Mindlessly eating heaping amounts of food, engulfing it without taking time to chew can cause you to feel bloated after meals and can lead you to eat more calories than your body may need. You do not have to count calories of every morsel you eat, but focus on eating more veggies (a fist full), lean protein (a palm size) and healthy starch (cupped handful) at every meal and eat slowly.

MY MORNING VITAMIN ROUTINE….

Every morning, there are a few key vitamins that I take and those are Vitamin D, C & B Complex. I take Vitamin A currently for my skin, cell health & immunity. 

Is it necessary to take vitamins everyday? Yes & no. We really should be getting what we can from our diets, given we are eating well-balanced nutritious foods. The thing is, most people are not,so in that case, supplementing may be needed. 

Vitamin D is a vitamin we simply can not get enough from diets alone, so supplementing is necessary. The minimum amount is currently 2500IU but most need more than that, especially if you are 40+, have inflammation/autoimmune or do not live in warm sunny environments. Vitamin D is critical for immunity, hormone balance, bone, skin and brain health to list only a few. 

B Complex is a mix of all the B vitamins which work best together. They are needed for energy production, metabolizing fats, carbs and proteins, nerve function, growth of red blood cells and so much more. 

Vitamin C is a very important vitamin. It is crucial for immune health, fights free radicals in the body, cellular health (mitochondrial function), and it also helps your body absorb and store iron. 
1000mg is recommended daily (more if you have autoimmune or different health issues .) 

Not shown here is Curcumin by @terrynaturallycanada that I take everyday to help reduce inflammation and for overall health of the body. Curcumin is a powerful spice that is an antioxidant and studied to help prevent many diseases. 

I do recommend having blood work taken at least 1x per year to know where you may be deficient and then possibly supplementing from there. Do not just take vitamins or supplements because the internet tells you to. Everyone is different and has different needs and the only way to know is to test! 😉

5 HEALTH HABITS I DO NOT RECOMMEND FOR WOMEN 35+

I’m a health coach who specializes in realistic, healthy weight/fat loss & guiding clients towards transforming their life for the long haul. Most of my clients are Women 35+ and these are my top 5 things I DO NOT recommend and why…

1. SKIPPING PROTEIN- protein is important for muscle mass, hormone function and overall bone health as we age. Always aim for 25-30 grams of protein at every meal (this is a base line amount…. needs will vary). 

2. Eating 1200 CALORIES OR LESS PER DAY- Unless you are a child, eating less than 1200 calories per day is not enough for adult females. Adequate calorie intake is important for hormone function and preventing muscle loss. Make the majority of your calories come from lean protein, healthy fats and whole-plant foods. 

3. EXCESSIVE HIIT WORKOUTS- Don’t shoot the messenger 🫣. Doing too many aggressive cardio, HIIT style sessions as we get older elevates our cortisol levels, which adds more stress to the body making fat loss more difficult and contributes to a slowed metabolic process and fatigued adrenal glands.

4. SKIPPING BREAKFAST(fasting)- Going long periods of time without eating, especially in the morning, can be harmful to female hormones. Breakfast within 2 hours of waking is important for balanced glucose levels and will prevent energy dips and sugar/carb cravings later in the day. 

5. TAKING QUICK FIXES/PRODUCTS-  I don’t recommend this for ANY age, but most gimmicks on the market promise you weight-loss, flat tummies etc. The truth is the only real way to lose weight/fat and maintain a healthy body is; 

✨ Develop healthy daily habits 
✨ Eat balanced nutritious meals
✨ Reduce your stress 
✨ Move your body daily (be sure to lift weights) 
✨ Eat protein at each meal

3 THINGS THAT COULD BE SABOTAGING YOUR WEIGHT-LOSS JOURNEY

When trying to lose weight in a realistic, sustainable manner, there are a few things I see as a Health Coach that sabotage most people’s success. I typically like to focus the attention towards how the client feels physically vs “weight” and these 3 things also tend to effect them physically too. 

1. COFFEE FOR BREAKFAST- If you wake up and run on coffee as your only source of fuel (especially if you are female over 35), this can be harmful for your hormone health. Coffee isn’t food but rather a stimulant and in most people, elevates cortisol, especially when no other food is present. Cortisol that remains elevated can be a contributing factor to why many struggle with stubborn weight. 

2. SKIPPING THE PROTEIN- Protein is needed in the body not only for building muscle but also for hormone function, energy, healing, and satiety. Start your day with a protein rich breakfast within 2 hours upon waking (not caffeine…) Aim for 25-30 grams of protein at every meal (this number may look different for each individual but it’s a good place to start.) 

3. DRINKING YOUR CALORIES- Calories are simply a source of energy and we do want that source to fuel our bodies efficiently. Drinking calories that have no nutritional value like sugary sodas, Starbucks drinks or even alcohol do not provide the body with nutrients and can contribute to weight gain IF it exceeds your calorie deficient for weight loss. Now, these drink can still fit into a well balanced diet (in moderation) but it’s very important to read labels and know what exactly is going into your body.

Here is my step-by-step for cleaning produce using vinegar and/or baking soda. 

1. Give your vegetables a good rinse in cold water to remove any dirt.

4. Rinse very well with cold water then place the produce over paper towel to dry them off a bit before using or storing in the fridge.

LONG WEEKEND REMINDER ☀️🦃

Holiday eating can create anxiety or fear for some of my clients who are on a new wellness journey to better their health. My job as a Health Coach is to show them that there is no need for restrictive behaviour around food and that all food choices can fit comfortably into their newly created healthy lifestyle. 

As we enter into this Thanksgiving long weekend, I’d like to share some tips I’ve given to my clients that you may benefit from as well. 

1. Plan ahead. Have a mini, protein-rich snack if dinner is far away from your last meal to prevent overeating and then feeling overly full. 

2. Eat to satisfy your hunger, not just because it’s in front of you. 

3. Take pleasure in your meal choices. Meals are sacred & a pleasure so do be sure to enjoy! 

4. Trust yourself! YOU are in control of your choices and if you do eat a bit more than you wanted to, will that truly be an issue in 1 year from now? Probably not, so move on 🤷🏻‍♀️

5. Chew properly. Chew slowly. Ask “Am I still hungry?” “Am I satisfied?” Put your fork down between bites to make this mindful connection with your body. 

Above all, get outside in this gorgeous sunny October weather we are still having here in Vancouver and enjoy time with loved ones! Remind yourself of everything you have to be thankful for 🫶🏼🙏🏼

5 WAYS TO INCREASE PROTEIN INTAKE

Protein is one of the main macronutrients and is essential for the health of our body. Protein is needed to build and repair tissues, muscles, cartilage and skin. Every body is very unique when it comes to discussing exactly how much protein one needs. 0.8g of protein per kg of body weight per day is what is recommended for the average adult. Chickpea Okra Stew Recipe

I am always preaching about meal prep, but even myself, as a Health Coach, have days where I did not prep enough food, and have been left scrambling at the last minute. If this sounds like you, then you are going to love this recipe! It is plant-based, and takes under 20 minutes to prepare.

SERVES 4
INGREDIENTS
1 tablespoon coconut oil 
1 medium yellow onion, diced
2 cloves garlic, minced 
2 cup chickpeas
2 cup okra
1 cup celery, chopped
1 can fire roasted tomatoes 
1 can (400 ml) full-fat coconut milk
2 tablespoon curry powder
1 teaspoon coriander 
1 teaspoon cumin
Dash cayenne pepper
Salt & pepper 
2 cups cooked jasmine rice 

DIRECTIONS

Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F. 

Rinse the frozen okra, well, and pat dry. Please onto a parchment lined paper baking sheet and drizzle a little olive oil over top. Add a little touch of salt and combine with your hands then place into the oven. Cook for 15 minutes.

Next, add the coconut oil to a pan, and then add the onions and garlic. Cook until golden and fragrant then the add the coconut milk, and fire roasted tomatoes. 

Remove the okra from the oven once it is done cooking. Add it immediately into the pan along with the chopped celery. Add in the spices, salt and pepper.

Stir everything well together, reduce the heat and cover with a lid. Cook on medium-to-low heat stirring occasionally for up to 10 minutes.

In this time frame, prepare your rice and have it ready.

Serve once everything is done by placing the rice first on the plate and the stew over top.

By understanding these truths about weight loss, you can approach your journey with a more informed perspective. Remember, sustainable weight loss is a gradual and long-term commitment that requires patience, perseverance, and a holistic approach to health and well-being.

5. You can still eat pizza and lose inches— Or cookies, cake, wine, whatever you like BUT, portion control and moderation is the key here 😉

Are you relying on just two eggs for your protein intake at each meal? While eggs are a great source of protein, they might not be enough to meet your daily protein needs.

If you want to bump up the protein profile on your eggs, try adding some liquid egg whites to them or some cottage cheese. This can take it from 6-12grams of protein all the way up to 25-30gr. 

If you make a salad and add 2 hard-boiled eggs, add some quinoa or tofu along with it to bump that protein up. In doing this, you will feel satiated for a much longer period of time than if you had eaten only the two or one egg. 

🌱 Five Protein Sources with 25gr+ Protein 🌱

1️⃣ Chicken Breast: Grilled chicken breast provides approximately 30g of lean protein per 100g serving.

2️⃣ Greek Yogurt: A single cup of Greek yogurt contains around 20-30g of protein, along with beneficial probiotics.

3️⃣ Tofu: A 150g serving of tofu offers roughly 30g of plant-based protein, making it an excellent option for vegetarians or vegans.

4️⃣ Quinoa: Cooked quinoa provides around 8g of protein per cooked cup, making it a protein-rich grain alternative.

5️⃣ Lentils: A cooked cup of lentils delivers about 18g of protein, making them a fantastic plant-based protein source.

Remember, by incorporating a variety of protein sources into your meals, you’ll not only meet your protein requirements but also enjoy the benefits of a balanced and varied diet.

Carbs have had a bad reputation for so long but I think many are very misinformed. 

Sustainable weight loss involves adopting healthy eating habits that can be maintained in the long term. Completely eliminating carbohydrates from your diet is often not sustainable and can lead to feelings of deprivation. This may increase the likelihood of giving in to cravings and overindulging, sabotaging your weight loss efforts. 

When you are a client of mine, I will never suggest you cut carbs and here is why…

1. Energy source: Carbohydrates are the body’s primary source of energy. They provide fuel for physical activity and help maintain optimal brain function. By including carbohydrates in your diet, you ensure that your body has the energy it needs to support your weight loss efforts and maintain overall well-being.

2. Nutrient-rich options: Many carbohydrate-rich foods, such as whole grains, fruits, and vegetables, are packed with essential vitamins, minerals, and dietary fiber. These nutrients are vital for maintaining good health and supporting various bodily functions. Cutting out carbohydrates may lead to nutrient deficiencies, which can negatively impact your overall health.

3. Satiety and satisfaction: Carbohydrates can contribute to feelings of fullness and satisfaction after a meal. Including complex carbohydrates, such as whole grains and legumes, can help you feel satisfied and prevent excessive hunger, which may lead to overeating or unhealthy food choices. This can be especially important when trying to adhere to a calorie-restricted diet for weight loss.

Have you tried the kitchen? It’s one of my favourite restaurants 😜.

All jokes, aside, let’s talk about the benefits of making food at home. Not only is it a healthier option, but it also saves you money in the long run!

By cooking at home, you have complete control over the ingredients you use. You can choose fresh and wholesome ingredients, avoid excessive salt, sugar, and unhealthy additives. Plus, cooking at home encourages portion control and you can re-purpose leftovers into delicious new meals the next day. 

Ingredients
Serves 1
1 cup of arugula
1/2 ripe avocado, sliced
4 ounces of wild salmon
1/4 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
1/4 cucumber, sliced or diced 
1 tbs Red onion, thinly sliced
Fresh parsley for garnish 

For the dressing (makes enough for 2-3 portions) 

Juice from 2 lemons
1 tbs fresh dill, chopped
4 tablespoons Greek yogurt
1 clove of fresh garlic, minced
1/4 tsp Salt and pepper 

Directions:

Preheat your oven to 400°F (200°C). Season the salmon with salt and pepper, then bake for about 12-15 minutes until cooked through.

In a bowl, arrange a bed of fresh arugula. Top it with sliced avocado, cherry tomatoes, cucumber and red onion.

In a separate bowl, mix together the lemon juice, chopped dill, Greek yogurt, salt, garlic, and pepper to make the dressing.

Place the cooked salmon on top of the veggies. Drizzle the dressing over the bowl.

Give it a gentle toss to combine all the ingredients and enjoy this nourishing salmon bowl!

Here are my tips on how to combat cravings when trying to lose weight… ⬇️⬇️

Understand that despite what others may say, CRAVING ARE NORMAL! If you are on health and/or weight loss journey, it’s pretty unrealistic to think you will never have a craving or even have any of your favourite foods again. 

But there are a few strategies that I teach my clients in my 30 Day Wellness Program. And while I’d love to give away ALL my strategies, I’ll have to save a few fav’s for when you join my program 😎

1. AVOID RESTRICTING- This often leads to feelings of deprivation, which can lead to binge eating and a negative relationship with food.

2. ENJOY ANYTHING IN MODERATION- Going with my above point, you do not want to feel deprived. So, you are better off having a small portion of whatever it is, enjoy and move on! I promise you will not ruin your progress nor will the world come to an end after enjoying a small portion here and there. 

3. THINK ABOUT YOUR CHOICES- Before you act on a choice, really STOP and THINK about your choice. Ask yourself “How will I feel after having this?” “Do I really want this? Or am I bored… (insert emotion)?” Then what I like to suggest is stepping away for about 15-20 minutes and tell yourself that if you still want it after 15-20 minutes, you can have it. This allows you to become mindful of choices you make rather than mindlessly grabbing and eating. 

✨Remember that ALL foods can fit into your health and wellness journey. It’s all about moderation!
